1. Data Structures & State (poke_logic.hpp)
You already have a fantastic start here with the PokemonInstance and character classes.

Inventory: In your character class, add integers to track the counts for potions, revives, and pokeballs. Set them to default starting values (e.g., 5 of each) in your character constructors.
Active Pokémon: Add an integer variable to your character class (e.g., active_pokemon_index) to track which of the 6 party members is currently battling.
HP Tracking: You already have current_hp and stats[0] (which acts as Max HP) in your PokemonInstance class, which is perfect. You will modify current_hp during battles.
2. The Battle UI and Loop (curse_main.cpp)
You already have placeholder functions battle_trainer and wild_encounter! This is where the core battle loop will live.

The Interface: Instead of just displaying the stats and waiting for ESC, update the ncurses window inside these functions to show a battle menu at the bottom with options for Fight, Bag, Run, and Pokemon.
The Turn Loop: Replace your while((ch = getch()) != 27) loop with the actual turn-based logic loop.
Wait for the PC to select a menu option.
If the player chooses Fight, prompt them to pick one of the moves from the active PokemonInstance's known_moves vector.
Generate the NPC's action (e.g., automatically pick "Fight" and choose a random move from their active Pokémon).
3. Executing Actions (Logic in poke_logic.cpp or inline in curse_main.cpp)
Once the inputs are gathered in the loop, execute the turn order.

Speed/Priority: Compare the priority of the chosen moves (you can get this from the moves struct pointer in known_moves). If priority ties, compare stats[5] (Speed) of both active PokemonInstances.
Damage Calculation: Create a helper function in poke_logic.cpp (e.g., calculate_damage()) that takes the attacking PokemonInstance, the defending PokemonInstance, and the chosen move.
Pull the Power, Accuracy, and Type from the move.
For the STAB (Same Type Attack Bonus) multiplier, look up the attacker's pokemon_id in your global all_pokemonTypes vector (from poke_data.cpp) to see if the move's type_id matches the Pokémon's type.
Apply the professor's damage formula using the attacker's stats[1] (Attack) and defender's stats[2] (Defense), roll for critical hit based on the attacker's base speed, and return the final damage integer.
Using Items: If the player picked Bag, decrement the appropriate inventory integer in the character object. If it's a Potion, add 20 to current_hp (capping at stats[0]). If it's a Revive, set a fainted Pokemon's current_hp to stats[0] / 2.
Fainting: At the end of every attack/action, check if either active Pokémon's current_hp is <= 0. If so, force that character to switch to the next valid Pokémon in their pokemon_party array. If an NPC has no conscious Pokémon left, set npc->isDefeated = 1 and break the loop.
4. Catching Pokémon (curse_main.cpp)
Inside wild_encounter, if the player uses a Pokéball from the Bag menu:

Check the player character's num_pokemon variable.
If it is less than 6, add the wild PokemonInstance to pokemon_party[num_pokemon], increment num_pokemon, and immediately end the battle (break the loop).
If it is 6, print a message that the Pokémon escaped, and decrement the Pokéball count.
5. Overworld Integration (curse_main.cpp)
You need to connect the world mechanics in your main() input switch statement:

PokeCenters: Look at your case '>': (around line 437). If curse_map->t[c->y][c->x].type == TERRAIN_POKEC, write a small for loop that iterates through the PC's pokemon_party array (up to num_pokemon) and resets current_hp = stats[0].
PokeMarts: In that exact same case '>', if the terrain is TERRAIN_POKEM, reset the PC's inventory variables back to their starting limits (e.g., 5).
The Bag Menu ('B'): Inside the switch(input) block for PC movement, add case 'B':. Create a new temporary ncurses window (like you did for the trainerPad) that lists the PC's pokemon_party array and allows them to consume Potions or Revives to heal outside of battle, updating current_hp accordingly.

formula for damage:

(((((2 * Level / 5) + 2) * Power * Attack/Defense) / 50) + 2) * Critical * random * STAB * Type

Escape Formula = floor(SpeedTrainer * 32/ floor(SpeedWild/4) mod256) + 30 * Attempts
SpeedTrainer = level-adjusted speed to the trainers' active pokemon
SpeedWild = level-adjusted speed to the wild pokemon
Attempts = num of attempts in this battle to escaped
this is out of 256, if rand() mod 256 < Escape Formula, the trainer escapes